        flourished under the early Ptolemies..."</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "Simmias, of Rhodes, Alexandrian poet and grammarian
        c. 300 BC (Suda s.v. &#x3A3;. &#x1FEC;&#x3CC;&#x3B4;&#x3B9;&#x3BF;&#x3C2;). Among his most important works are the &#x393;&#x3BB;&#x1FF6;&#x3C3;&#x3C3;&#x3B1;&#x3B9;/Gl&#xF4;ssai
        ('Glosses', 3 books) and a collection of poetry (&#x3A0;&#x3BF;&#x3B9;&#x3AE;&#x3BC;&#x3B1;&#x3C4;&#x3B1; &#x3B4;&#x3B9;&#x3AC;&#x3C6;&#x3BF;&#x3C1;&#x3B1;/Poi&#x1E17;mata di&#xE1;phora, 4
        books), both surviving in only few fragments. S. is considered to be the inventor of
        technopa&#xED;gnia and several lyric metres....." Baumbach, Manuel (Z&#xFC;rich). "Simias." Brill's
        New Pauly. Antiquity volumes edited by: Hubert Cancik and Helmuth Schneider. Brill, 2009. </mads:note>
